      "writtenOn": "2020-11-03T08:36:07Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "this is not a good allocation pattern.  it assumes that the syscall table is always rooted at 0, generally increases monotonically, and is generally small.  arm32 for example has syscall numbers like 983045 which means this will allocate 3,932,180 bytes just for the array of pointers.  x32 has even larger syscall numbers.\n\nfurther, this code is buggy.  it assumes that the syscall map is linear (starting at 0) and has no holes.  get_num_syscalls returns the number of syscalls, not the nr values themselves which can be much larger.",
      "revId": "a8041ae085c3dd8ae967e6acda1af1cfd5d5c4c5",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
